3c

The variance covariance matrix for the model m1 in 3a and m2 in 3b are very similar.

The model for the m1 is lme with only the intercept. Yij = beta0 + beta1*ti+…+b1i+error

The merginal mean response is beta0 + beta1ti+…+ betapxij and it is the same as the Compound Symmetry model.

anova(m5,m7)

## m7     2 12 12424.34 12488.20 -6200.172 1 vs 2 1.631394  0.4423

since the p value =0.4423 and is greater than 0.05, so we cannot reject the null hypothesis. Which means there is no significant contribution of genotype to the change in FEV1 over time.

#5c
m8 =  lme(FEV1 ~ AGE+FEMALE+F508_1+F508_2+AGEL*FEMALE, data=df2,method="ML",
          random= ~ AGEL | ID) 
anova(m5,m8)
##    Model df      AIC      BIC    logLik   Test  L.Ratio p-value
## m5     1 10 12421.98 12475.19 -6200.988                        
## m8     2 11 12419.82 12478.36 -6198.912 1 vs 2 4.152138  0.0416

since the p value =0.0416 and is smaller than 0.05, so we reject the null hypothesis. Which means there is a significant contribution of gender to the change in FEV1 over time. Choose m8 as the best model.

pred8 <- data.frame(id=df2$ID,female=df2$FEMALE,age=df2$AGE,
                     pred=fitted(m8, level=0), resid=cr.8[,1])
ggplot(pred8, aes(x=resid))+
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), color="black", fill="lightblue") +
  geom_density() + labs(title="Distribution of Transformed Residuals-LME m8", x="Residual")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

  geom_point() + geom_hline(yintercept=0,colour="red") +
  geom_smooth(method="loess", se=F) +
  labs(title="Scatter Plot of Transformed Residual against Predicted Mean-LME m4.4",
       x="Predicted Mean", y="Residual")
